words: It was a bit of a rocky road 'til I got that letter and it
really had a big impact on me. Uh I'll start off by saying that
I'm from Guyana and I finished high school there. And in Guyana you graduate
in eleventh grade. Um Guyana doesn't have as many opportunities like
the clubs and the AP classes and that kind of thing. So, I really wanted to
go back to the US to do twelfth grade since in Guyana twelfth grade's optional. So I
figured I'd be able to do twelfth grade in the US and you know do those APs,
uh join the clubs, get volunteer hours, all that stuff, make the college resume look really nice.
Um and also just because I wanted to do more. So,
we went over to Miami, Florida and went to the school and requested to
be enrolled. And they told me since I graduated already I can't enroll. And I was
like oh, well crap, what am I going to do. So, I ended up having this accidental
gap year where I, where I just did my SATs, my SAT subject test,
like learn to drive, did some reading, that kind of thing. And I was like I guess hopefully
what I have so far is enough to get into a good college. Um
I had gotten a few rejections that I didn't expect like
from Duke and Johns Hopkins and Cornell and Georgia Tech.
And those, all these rejections were before my acceptance to Stanford. And
so I was in a pretty low spot. Uh I really wanted to go to the University of Miami and I
had applied there as well 'cause that's where I was expecting to be able to go. And what
happened was they told me since I didn't do twelfth grade that I would have to
go to community college for a year before I could go to um their university.
And it just felt like such a huge step back to do that so that was the position I was in at the time.
Probably going to community college before I could go to University of Miami since all, I didn't really
have much options. And then my mom was checking her email and
she saw the email that said congratulations we
so happy to inform you that you got accepted. And she's
like, told me like come over here. I was in the kitchen getting like Rice Krispies or something. Told me come over here, come
over here. And I read it and I was in total shock. I thought it was spam and
it just, it felt so good to finally have something go in the right direction.
And like one of the best universities in the world. I couldn't believe that that was the one that I got accepted to when
I was getting all these rejections. I never even thought I would get into Stanford in the first place. That was the
